                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@EOF: Yes, insane and dangerous (for your process, not the system).   You can already do that without the kernel&apos;s help, with a far &lt;code&gt;jmp&lt;/code&gt; using the known value of the kernel&apos;s segment selectors (&lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/34467092/inline-64bit-assembly-in-32bit-gcc-c-program#comment56677286_34467109&quot; title=&quot;inline 64bit assembly in 32bit gcc c program%23comment56677286_34467109&quot;&gt;stackoverflow.com/questions/34467092/&lt;/a&gt;).  AFAIK it&apos;s not useful, or supported under Linux, but you can do it.  There&apos;s even a &lt;code&gt;modify_ldt&lt;/code&gt; system call that lets you do it in a &quot;standard&quot; way: &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/a/13355668/224132&quot;&gt;stackoverflow.com/a/13355668/224132&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

