            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;The zeroing of &lt;code&gt;r8-r11&lt;/code&gt; I don&apos;t believe is guaranteed on old unpatched kernels. Seem to recall that this was part of a data bleed vulnerability at one time when you had a 32-bit program do an &lt;code&gt;int 0x80&lt;/code&gt; and then switched to 64-bit code and gained access to the previous values of those registers.I think their fix was to zero them out prior to returning. You sort of mention it in the answer, but I believe you&apos;ll find a an actual vulnerability associated with it if you search.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/3857942/michael-petch&quot; title=&quot;43,996 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;Michael Petch&lt;/a&gt;
                &lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment81177763_46087731&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2017-11-04 18:16:03Z, License: CC BY-SA 3.0&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Nov 4, 2017 at 18:16&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
                        &lt;span title=&quot;this comment was edited 1 time&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;va-text-bottom o50 svg-icon iconPencilSm&quot; width=&quot;14&quot; height=&quot;14&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 14 14&quot;&gt;&lt;path d=&quot;m11.1 1.71 1.13 1.12c.2.2.2.51 0 .71L11.1 4.7 9.21 2.86l1.17-1.15c.2-.2.51-.2.71 0ZM2 10.12l6.37-6.43 1.88 1.88L3.88 12H2v-1.88Z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
